 of the house, the mosaics become eloquent witnesses to an elusive dialogue between inhabitants and guests, and to the intermingling of public and private. Kondoleon draws on the insights of art history and archaeology to show what the mosaics in the House of Dionysos can tell us about these complex relations. She explores the issues of period and regional styles, workshop traditions, the conditions of patronage, and the forces behind iconographic change. Her work marks a major advance, not just in the study of Roman mosaics, but in our knowledge of Roman society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aMosaics, RomanzCypruszPaphos. 0aMythology, Greek, in art. 0aPavements, MosaiczCypruszPaphos. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501727412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501727412.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG